I think it's because AEW posed as an "ethical" alternative to WWE. They pretend to be more progressive, being a little more forward with the LGBT marketing (except their women's roster is shit and doesn't get screen time and they misgender their they/them wrestler on commentary all the time). All that stuff about how you don't get a no-compete clause, how you get more time off for injuries, aren't fired when injured, about how you can still wrestle at other companies, don't have to pretend only the WWE universe exist, about how you've got more say in your character (think FTR and the new gear that was suggested for them at WWE or Ambrose's frustration at his character). It's many things that are on the one hand simply better for wrestlers on the other also always implicitly criticize the way WWE is run. You also have a roster of ex WWE people, some of them who've been quite open about what they dislike about WWE or how they've been wronged (Mox, Bryan, Punk). While recent developments with Phil and the Bucks have made people question some of that narrative (and really... never trust a company that says it's like a family), AEW still poses as an alternative to WWE where wrestlers have more creative freedom and aren't exploited as much. This might explain some of the rift.

She lay on her bed, feeling miserable and alone, regretting the choices she had made. She knew that she had hurt the people she cared about, and that she had only herself to blame for the pain she was feeling.

In the end, Momo learned that being selfish only leads to loneliness and regret, and that true happiness comes from sharing and caring for others. She vowed to never be selfish again, and to always think of the needs of others before her own.

>>8286397
ratio is your download vs upload. a ratio of 1 would equal you uploading 100% of the amount of data you downloaded. If you downloaded 10GB or 300GB you seeded back that same amount to have a 1 ratio. You generally want to have a ratio above a 1. This is achieved by seeding the torrent for many weeks and snagging some late comers.

xwt offers dozens and dozens of freeleech packs that will help you establish a positive ratio while you download the shit you really want. I recommend high traffic megapacks like WWF and WCW ppv collections, or full year packs of companies like NJPW. Remember, you don't have to download every file in those megapacks to generate an upload. For example, I only have 6GB of the entire 588GB torrent of WCW Saturday Night but have gotten over 650GB of upload in its 5 month lifespan.

Generally if you don't seed a 1:1 then having seeded a torrent for 3 days is enough to avoid getting the ire of the mods.

I recommend qbittorrent as a good torrent program, there's some quality of life improvements for the UI over others like utorrent.

xwt has gone invite only for the first time in its 15 years though to look like it's a credible tracker. (it's not, there's not even a bonus point system that's standard for everything) so you might wanna ask a friend or maybe they'll open up registrations for new years

For the sake of joshi preservation, I'll help you out.
The old Chrome Extension that everybody used, Video Downloader Pro, still detects and downloads videos fine on VK. However, Google banned it from the Extension store and forcefully disabled it in the browser due to "security concerns" and "malware", i.e. piracy - protecting the copyright of content creators.
However, it's still usable. I don't remember exactly how I did this because it was several months ago, but I found a previous version of the extension on a website, downloaded it, and installed it to Chrome manually by dropping it into the folder so it doesn't connect to the official Google store at all and they can't directly disable it. This also means you won't get mandatory updates.
This process involved messing around with CRX files, which I wasn't familiar with, and deleting some metadata, but eventually I did it. The guy who was confused about torrents probably wouldn't have the patience for it, but I'm an autistic joshi hoarder so I didn't have a choice.
To spare you the same hassle, I've zipped my version of the app and uploaded it below. I don't know how you feel about downloading strange zip files from the internet but there's no exe inside so it should be clean on a virus scan. Drop it into the folder in the image I've attached and it should work fine. The app will appear in the extensions section of your browser just like a regular app from the store.
